[1] Vaccine hesitancy commentary
Date: Tue 11 Jun 2019
From: Peter English <Peter.English@phe.gov.uk> [edited]


re: ProMED-mail Measles update (41) 20190610.6512991
[1] National, Idaho, Virginia
----------------------------------------------------
"Federal health officials attribute 2019's outbreak to parents who refuse to vaccinate their children..." This concerns me.

Reports blaming vaccine hesitancy for low uptake may help drive understanding of how to address vaccine hesitancy. But they have adverse consequences: they make it easier for people to blame vaccine hesitancy when they should be blaming inadequate vaccination services (and funding better services); and, for those people who are hesitant, it may also validate their concerns -- "lots of other people are refusing vaccines believing them to be unsafe, so there must be something in it..."

For most of us, in everyday practice, tackling vaccine hesitancy means following the simple rules outlined to me by Dr David Elliman (I hope I'm characterizing them in a way he would recognize!):
1. Most people are content to be or have their children vaccinated, and long discussion is unnecessary and counter-productive.
2. A few have reasonable concerns that can easily be addressed.
3. Some have a quasi-religious antipathy to vaccination. These people may only have come to try to convince you that vaccination is harmful! For these people there's no point in trying to address specific concerns -- it may even harden their position. The best response is simply to say "Vaccination is the best way to protect your self/child. I realize that you don't agree, but if you change your mind, come back at any time and you/your child can then be vaccinated."

Tackling poor uptake for other reasons, however, is hard work. It requires good population databases, excellent systems for call and recall, finding ways to identify people having difficulty making it to appointments and to reach out to them. (The term "tail-gunning" was invented for identifying the (usually relatively few) people on a list of people who hadn't had their vaccines and following them up.)

Remember the Jewish community in North London? It was assumed they had some religious or cultural objection to vaccination. Actually, they had very large families; and if you don't have a lot of money, and you have a lot of children, simply getting to the clinic (GP surgery) for the vaccine is really difficult.

Reaching out to people and making vaccination easy costs money, at a time when austerity measures have had a cumulative effect. They tend to hit the community services first. If hospital beds close, there's an outcry. If you cut back on health visiting and vaccination services, most people don't notice.

So as vaccine (and public health) advocates, we need to keep pressing for investment in and improvements to vaccination services; and not fall prey to victim-blaming talk of vaccine hesitancy.

--
Dr Peter M B English
Consultant in Communicable Disease Control
<peter.english@phe.gov.uk>

[ProMED thanks Dr. English for his commentary. - Mod.LL]

