[2] New York City: school closure
Date: Tue 11 Jun 2019 5:29 PM ET
Source: New York Daily News [edited]
http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/ny-williamsburg-yeshiva-closed-by-city-health-measles-outbreak-20190611-rmveg7kzcrb7rhv7sfm3nopggu-story.html


Months into a measles epidemic, [New York] city health officials said they were forced on Tue 11 Jun 2019, to shut down a Brooklyn yeshiva for failing to comply with emergency measures to curb the ongoing outbreak. The number of cases citywide hit 588, according to the Health Department.

One of the United Talmudical Academy's 4 locations -- Central UTA Boys Division at 762 Wythe Ave. in Williamsburg -- was shuttered when the school didn't bar students and staff who didn't have proof they were inoculated with the measles-mumps-rubella vaccine, officials said. The school was also hit with violations for failing to have enough staff present for students and for not providing health inspectors with vaccination and attendance records, according to the agency. The yeshiva can't reopen until the school can prove it has complying with Health Department mandates.

The phone operator at Central UTA Boys Division hung up on the Daily News on Tuesday afternoon, 11 Jun 2019, and another call seeking comment was not returned.

The yeshiva is the 10th school the city has closed down since the Health Department ordered all people who live, work, or go to school in 4 Williamsburg zip codes be vaccinated or risk fines. The other 9 schools have already reopened.

The United Talmudical Academy in Williamsburg was previously hit with USD 13 000 in fines for 11 violations at 4 different locations in May 2019.

"School staff, parents, and healthcare providers need to continue playing their role in bringing this outbreak to an end," Health Commissioner Oxiris Barbot said in a statement. "We've seen our weekly case counts decline, but the reality is this outbreak is not over, and the Health Department will continue to use all the resources and strategies available to us. We urge anyone who can get vaccinated to do so."

Nationwide, there have been 1022 confirmed cases of measles in 2019 through 6 Jun 2019, according to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.

The city's measles outbreak began in October 2018, hitting Orthodox Jewish communities in Brooklyn hardest. Of the 588 cases to date across the 5 boroughs, 74%, or 437, occurred in Williamsburg zip codes where the vaccination order is in place. The city has so far slapped 173 individuals with summonses for failing to comply with the vaccination order, risking USD 1000 penalties, according to the Health Department. 68 of those were eventually scrapped after the individuals showed proof of immunity or got vaccinated.

